# Text Elements
Consider an incompressible flow, laminar boundary layer growing along the surface of a
flat plate, with chord length c, as sketched in Figure 2.23. The definition of a boundary
layer was discussed in Sections 1.10 and 1.11. For an incompressible, laminar, flat plate
boundary layer, the boundary-layer thickness δ at the trailing edge of the plate is ^iDH8uyYk

and the skin friction drag coefficient for the plate is  ^MzktBQuC

where the Reynolds number is given as : ^br70aCfY

We assume the velocity profile through the boundary 
layer is given by a power-law variation ^sUfxPvVv

calculate the value of n
consistent with the information given above ^Roq8dtrw

Note the flow is low-speed and incompressible, hence 
the Mach number is not a relevant number here ^c3g9778O

Solution: ^NSlZ0EpL


# Embedded files
7a57fc5fd976c64509ac55bfe3868113ac2eb346: $$\frac{\delta}{c} = \frac{5}{\sqrt{Re_c}}$$
b094585f73ea78cb1ca092e6742108fe1b08d407: $$C_f \equiv \frac{D'}{q_\infty c(1)}$$
5eaa86c18616827715f4937ba062a6dc3e0940eb: $$Re = \frac{\rho V_\infty c}{\mu}$$
a83d4d986290c7bac0515ce39b50c3fe645c7dd9: $$u = V_\infty (\frac{y}{\delta})^n$$
